Plotting with Idyll and Vega-lite

By: Joram Mutenge
Apr 16, 2022

Human Freedom Index

The plots below are created from the Human Freedom Index (HFI) dataset. It comes from the United Nations and Freedom House. HFI is an annual report that evaluates the state of human freedom in 165 countries and territories around the world, representing 98.1 percent of the human population as of 2021.

The HFI measures both personal and economic freedom, then merges the two into a single value called “human freedom.”

Eight variables make up the dataset. These are:

  • country
  • year
  • CL (civil liberties)
  • PR (political rights)
  • Status (Free F, Not Free NF, Partially Free PF)
  • Region_Code
  • Region_Name
  • is_ldc (Is a least developed country (binary 0/1))
Download the dataset.

Scrolling through many rows of data can be quite distructing. To tackle this problem, I have loaded the dataset so that it only shows 10 rows per page.

Bar plot of Region vs Political Rights (PR)


In this bar chart, I wanted to see which region had the most political rights. The higher the value, the less political rights. I didn’t expect Asia to have the same score as Europe. It turns out Oceania has the most political rights.

Political rights (PR) across the world


In this graph, I wanted to see the change in political rights across the world over the years. The y-axis is an aggregate of all the PR values from all the countries. Hence, the lower the bar, the more political rights. There hasn’t been much change but we can see that between 2002 and 2006, the was more political freedom around the world. Unfortunately, there has been a steady decline in PR beginning 2013 as indicated by the higher bar values.

Political rights vs Civil liberties

Color by:


This is an interactive graph of political rights as a function of civil liberties. The buttons underneath the graph are clickable. For example, clicking Status identifies which dots represents Free (F), Not Free (NF), or Partially Free (PF). As expected, the dots representing free have lower CL and PR scores. Likewise, clicking the Region button identifies the dots represented by each region. Unsurprisingly, the green dots representing Oceania have lower scores for both CL and PR. The None button returns the normal graph.
